Introduction We chose to analyze San Francisco [SF] for this week’s assignment. More specifically, we wanted to understand which neighborhoods supported the city’s green and sustainable goals most and aligned with that. In order to do that we chose the following datasets:

Points: A) Urban Trees (this is a data set that excludes trees in parks specifically) B) Bike Stations (this is derived from the Bike Network data set) B2) Green Roofs (this is an extra layer we wanted to use)

Polygons: C) Neighborhoods D) Parks

Potential areas of future research could include adding a layer of racial data in addition to other demographic data to lead to deeper insights.

Mapping All the Data

#Loading Data

nbhoods <- st_read("https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/pty2-tcw4?method=export&format=GeoJSON" , quiet = TRUE)

bikenetwork <- st_read("https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/msjm-67c8?method=export&format=GeoJSON", quiet = TRUE)

greenroofs <- st_read("https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/x83m-rafs?method=export&format=GeoJSON" , quiet = TRUE)

parks <- st_read("https://data.sfgov.org/api/geospatial/42rw-e7xk?method=export&format=GeoJSON", quiet = TRUE)

trees <- read.csv(file = 'Street_Tree_List.csv')
#Transform Coordinate Plane for KML dataset

ca_state_plane <- "+proj=lcc +lat_1=40 +lat_2=41.66666666666666 +lat_0=39.33333333333334 +lon_0=-122 +x_0=2000000 +y_0=500000.0000000002 +ellps=GRS80 +datum=NAD83 +to_meter=0.3048006096012192 +no_defs "

nbhoods <- nbhoods %>%
  st_transform(ca_state_plane)

bikenetwork <- bikenetwork %>%
  st_transform(ca_state_plane)

greenroofs <- greenroofs %>%
  st_transform(ca_state_plane)

parks <- parks %>%
  st_transform(ca_state_plane) %>%
filter(map_park_n != "Camp Mather")
#Converting Coordinate System for CSV dataset

trees_csv <- read.csv(file = "https://data.sfgov.org/api/views/tkzw-k3nq/rows.csv?accessType=DOWNLOAD")

trees_csv <- trees_csv %>%
  drop_na(c("Latitude", "Longitude")) 

trees_sf <- st_as_sf(trees_csv, coords = c("Longitude", "Latitude"),
                     crs = "+proj=longlat +ellps=WGS84 +datum=WGS84 +no_defs") %>% 
  
  st_transform(ca_state_plane) 
#Sub-setting

trees_inside <- trees_sf[nbhoods,]
parks_inside <- parks[nbhoods,]
#Plotting All Data

ggplot(nbhoods) +
  geom_sf(fill = NA, color = "gray") +
  geom_sf(data = trees_inside , size = 0.01, alpha = 0.01) +
  geom_sf(data = greenroofs, size = 0.2) +
  geom_sf(data= parks_inside, fill = "black", color = NA, alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_sf(data= bikenetwork, fill = NA, color = "orange", size = 0.3) +
  theme_map() +
  annotation_scale()

Map 1: (5) The number and proportion of A points within C polygons

How many of the urban tress [A] are within each SF neighborhood [C]?

#Counting urban trees within neighborhoods

nbhoods <- nbhoods %>%
  mutate(num_trees_inside = lengths(st_covers(nbhoods, trees_inside))) 

ggplot(nbhoods) +
  geom_sf(color = NA, 
          aes(fill = num_trees_inside)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "SF neighborhoods\nby number of trees",
                       breaks = breaks <- seq(0, 10000, by = 1000),
                       labels = paste(prettyNum(breaks, big.mark = ","),
                                      "trees")) +
  annotation_scale(location = "br") +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "tl",
                         style = north_arrow_minimal()) +
theme_map() +
  theme(legend.background = element_rect(fill = alpha("white", 0.5), 
                                         color = "gray"))

This can help shed light on how resources are being concentrated in the San Francisco neighborhood and serve as a point of information directing the government on how to allocate resources to encourage adoption of green-roofs in neighborhoods that do not have green-roofs.

Note: An interesting point to note is that density has a different impact on the map as opposed to comparing absolute data. This is highlighted though the change in color of the map where the smaller neighborhood becomes yellow compared to the larger neighborhood which was initially yellow when measuring absolutes (refer to graph above). These two maps together serve as a cautionary tale, to check whether the map illustrates max. green roofs in a certain neighborhood or because of size of that neighborhood effecting density.

Map 5:

(14)The number and proportion of C polygons that overlap with D polygons

The number and proportion of Neighborhoods [C] that have Parks in them [D] = 45 Percentage = 38.46%

This map makes clear which neighborhoods lack open, green spaces.

nbhoods <- nbhoods %>%
  mutate(num_parks_inside = lengths(st_overlaps(nbhoods, parks_inside))) %>%
  mutate(has_parks_inside = num_parks_inside > 0)

n_parks_inside_Nbhoods <- sum(nbhoods$has_parks_inside)

n_parks_inside_Nbhoods
## [1] 45
pct_parks_inside_nbhoods <- n_parks_inside_Nbhoods / nrow(nbhoods)
pct_parks_inside_nbhoods
## [1] 0.3846154
left_side  <- st_bbox(parks_inside)$xmin
top_side <- st_bbox(parks_inside)$ymax

ggplot(parks_inside) +
  geom_sf(fill = "lightblue", color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = nbhoods,
          aes(fill = has_parks_inside)) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("darkred", "cornsilk1"),
          name = "SF Neighborhood\nby presence of Parks", 
          labels = c("Neighborhood without any Parks",
                     "Neighborhood with Parks")) +
  annotation_scale(location = "br") +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "tl",
                         style = north_arrow_minimal()) +
  annotate(geom = "text", x = left_side + 4000, 
           y = top_side + 6000, 
           label = paste(n_parks_inside_Nbhoods ,
                         "of SF's", 
                         length(nbhoods$name),
                         "Neighborhood contain\n", 
                         "parks."),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 0, size = 3) +
  theme_map() +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "gray"),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = alpha("white", 0.5), 
                                         color = "gray"))

Map 6: (1) The number and proportion of A points within a specified distance of B points

The number and proportion of Urban Trees [A] at distance of 100m from Bike Stations[B] = 45 Percentage = 2%

This map helps understand which of the bike stands are most shaded.

bike_buffer <- st_buffer(bikenetwork, dist = 100) %>%
  st_union()

ggplot(bike_buffer) +
  geom_sf ()

#Subsetting
trees_inside_bike <- trees_inside[bike_buffer,]
  
ggplot(bike_buffer) +
  geom_sf() +
  geom_sf(data = trees_inside_bike, 
          color = "darkgreen", 
          size = 0.01) +
  theme_map()

trees_inside <- trees_inside %>%
  st_join(trees_inside_bike)%>%
  mutate(by_bike = !is.na(XCoord.y))

n_bike_trees_inside <- sum(trees_inside$by_bike)
n_bike_trees_inside
## [1] 4658
pct_bike_trees_inside <- n_bike_trees_inside/nrow(trees_inside)
pct_bike_trees_inside
## [1] 0.02383328

#Plotting Data

left_side  <- st_bbox(trees_inside)$xmin
top_side <- st_bbox(trees_inside)$ymax

ggplot(nbhoods) +
  geom_sf(fill = NA , color = 'black') +
  geom_sf(data = trees_inside, size = 0.02,
          aes(color = by_bike)) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("lightgreen", "darkgreen"),
          name = "SF Trees\nby distance to a bike station", 
          labels = c("No Tree within 100 m",
                     "Tree within 100 m")) +
  annotation_scale(location = "br") +
  annotation_north_arrow(location = "tr",
                         style = north_arrow_minimal()) +
  annotate(geom = "text", x = left_side, 
           y = top_side + 5000, 
           label = paste("Of the 50000 ",
                         " trees in SF ", 
                          prettyNum(n_bike_trees_inside, big.mark = ","),
                         " (", 
                         prettyNum(100*pct_bike_trees_inside, digits = 0),
                         "%) are within 100\nmeters of a parking meter.",
                         sep = ""),
           hjust = 0, vjust = 0, size = 3) +
  theme_map() +
  theme(panel.background = element_rect(fill = "cornsilk1"),
        legend.background = element_rect(fill = alpha("white", 0.5), 
                                         color = "gray"))
